ADR-0001: Cross-Platform Smart IME Core
# ADR-0001: Core Language Choice for Smart IME

## Status
Accepted

## Context
We are building an offline Smart IME that:
- Runs on Windows and Android
- Detects CL-style input vs Japanese natural language
- Performs post-input classification
- Requires low latency
- Must work fully offline

## Decision
Use Rust as the core language processing engine.

Platform adapters:
- Windows: C++ bridge (Win32 / TSF IME)
- Android: Kotlin + JNI bridge to Rust

## Rationale

### Why not pure C++?
- Cross-platform complexity
- Memory safety concerns
- Harder Android integration

### Why not pure Java/Kotlin?
- Performance cost for NLP classification
- Harder reuse on Windows native layer

### Why Rust?
- Memory safe
- High performance
- Easy FFI to C++ and Java (JNI)
- Single shared core logic

## Consequences

Positive:
- Shared detection engine
- Deterministic performance
- Safer memory model

Negative:
- JNI complexity
- Windows IME API learning curve
README.md
# SmartIME (Post-Detection IME)

Offline AI-assisted IME that auto-detects:
- Command Line style input (CL)
- Japanese natural language
- Mixed-language prompts

## Concept

Traditional IME requires mode switching before typing.

SmartIME works differently:

1. Accept raw romaji input
2. Analyze text after commit
3. Classify intent:
   - CLI / Code
   - Japanese sentence
   - Mixed prompt
4. Transform output accordingly

No manual mode switching.

## Architecture

Core Engine (Rust)
    ↓
Windows Adapter (C++ / TSF)
Android Adapter (Kotlin + JNI)

## Detection Strategy (Offline)

- Character distribution model
- Token pattern detection
    - `--`, `/`, `$`, `git`, `npm`, etc.
- Japanese romaji probability model
- Context window from previous inputs

## Offline NLP

No LLM required.
Use:
- N-gram language model
- Small logistic classifier
- Optional tiny transformer (quantized)

Target latency:
< 10ms per classification

## Future Extensions

- Local tiny embedding model
- Personal dictionary learning
- Context-aware prediction

## Why This Matters

IME should not be a state machine.
It should be a probabilistic language router.
